Summary:

King’s Landing University is the premier university of Westeros, only accepting the most elite of applicants. At KLU, the most important activity of them all is Greek Life. Each year, the Houses vie for the top spot on KLU’s Greekrank Tier List that comes out at the end of the spring term — based on who has the best parties, the highest recruitment numbers, and, most importantly, who wins at the end of Sigma Chi’s Greek Week.
The Starks have long controlled Kappa Theta Mu and Psi Epsilon Mu, now known as House Stark, and it is expected that freshmen Sansa and Arya join. However, Sansa has been eyeing House Lannister’s Kappa Iota Gamma sorority. Will Sansa stick with her family, or will she join the shining Lannisters as one of the Kappas?
In the meantime, Daenerys Targaryen and her brother Viserys are on a mission to reinstate their family’s ancestral charters of Chi Omega and Omega Zeta Lambda; the Baratheon hold at the top of the tier system is in jeopardy as the Deltas crumble; Jon Snow gets courted by the reputable underground frat, Sigma Nu, or the Night’s Watch; House Tyrell and the Sigmas sit back and enjoy the show as the other houses fight; and Theta Chi is on the rise — or so say the Theta Chi Greyjoys.

summary: maybe i’m being influenced the fact that my country and homeland were colonised by europeans and ravaged by US interventionism...
question: maybe i’m being influenced the fact that my country and homeland were colonised by europeans and ravaged by US interventionism but my respect for sansa went up this season. i always had a lot of respect for her but the fact that she looked a  tyrannical invader, who was capable of destroying the entire continent with her wmd, in the eye and said, ‘not the north bitch,’ almost made me cry from pride. she deserved to be queen.
answer:
RIGHT.

Like, that’s also why Dany/Sansa just doesn’t work as a ship at all! One party is very intent on destroying everything the other party has fought and bled for years on end and it makes zero sense why Sansa would just like … give up the her home to someone she doesn’t trust who demands unconditional fealty and also has weapons of mass destruction. 

Plus like, while Dany’s all “I’m not a politician I’m a queen,” Sansa’s like “I don’t care what you want to call me, call me a direwolf if you want, but I want to keep my people alive and happy.” Also like, the “GoT hates women’s ambition!!!!” argument falls short when you consider that Sansa’s ambitious as well and she doesn’t destroy cities and murder people for it!!!! Like by season 6, she knows that she’s smart and capable and strong in her own way and she wants to use those skills to help her people, which is textbook ambition, the belief in one’s own worth and capability to rule. And even that is enough to make Jon say disparagingly that Sansa thinks she’s the smartest person in the room and that she’s starting to let on that she’s smart despite the fact it’s Dany who’s the one who demands fealty from all who are around her. Sansa might think she’s smart but why is that such a bad thing when she’s been proven to be more than competent? Thankfully, Arya defended her sister because Jon was clearly not thinking straight.

Anyways yeah, I’m buying my Sansa 2020 t-shirt soon and I hope you do too!

tags: I hate to break it to you but d&d are just bad writers
they haven't been playing the long con of how to make Sansa look smart from season one lmao
summary: don't you ever think about how characters like tyrion, petyr baelish, jon and arya were dumbed down to make Sansa seem smart?
question: don't you ever think about how characters like tyrion, petyr baelish, jon and arya were dumbed down to make Sansa seem smart?
answer:
don’t you ever wonder if character’s like baelish and tyrion (and also cersei) weren’t written as smart in the later seasons (after running out of source material), even when they were nowhere near Sansa, was because d&d did not know how to write smart, ruthless, manipulative villains who would make moves that shocked the audience? 

don’t you ever wonder if Tyrion, an actual villain in the books, and Jon were were written as purely good and heroic even if it meant dumbing them down and reducing their characters, was to prop them up as characters we were supposed to root for over the “mad manipulative women”?

don’t you ever think about how from day one they always saw Arya as a “I don’t like other girls because I’m different” murder child rather than the intelligient feminist that she is? because they don’t know how to write complex female characters?

These writing changes and messed up characterisation wasn’t because they wanted to make Sansa look smart - most of them weren’t even interacting with Sansa when these writing problems began. 

I hate to break it to you but Sansa was always smart. She survived based on her intelligence and also her kindness, she knows how to play the game and has been ever since book/season one. Nobody needs to be dumbed down to prove how smart Sansa is because she’s been proving it herself this whole time but you obviously didn’t care enough to pay attention to her.

summary:
Sansa x Jeyne: Winterfell

After the war was over Sansa had rushed to Winterfell to see the truth of the rumors of her missing...
body:
Sansa x Jeyne: Winterfell


After the war was over Sansa had rushed to Winterfell to see the truth of the rumors of her missing sister. When she arrived it was not Arya she found—but Jeyne, her sweet, pretty, wonderful Jeyne. Her family might be lost to her still-but maybe Sansa wouldn’t be alone after all.


A gift for @wedonnotcare
